\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: concepts"

\end_inset

Concepts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When moving from a PCW to an emulator, the biggest change you have to accustom
 yourself to is the way that JOYCE handles discs.
 Real PCWs (except the few with add-on hard drives) use real floppy discs;
 you use a start-of-day disc to use LocoScript or MicroDesign, a data disc
 to save your work on, and so on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is possible for JOYCE to use real disc drives in the same way that a
 PCW does.
 However this is pretty slow and awkward; since the PC's got a hard drive,
 you might as well use it.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Disc image files
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
PCW programs can't generally use the PC's hard drive directly.
 For one thing, it's too big; and for another, it's not in CP/M format
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
If you do happen to have a CP/M partition on your hard drive, I don't want
 to know.
 JOYCE still won't use it.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Instead, JOYCE creates one or more 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

disc image files
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Each of these is the equivalent of one real PCW disc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Disc image files have a number of advantages:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
They are much faster than real floppy discs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
You don't have to be shuffling a stack of floppies every time you want to
 use JOYCE.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If you want more discs, you don't have to go to the shop to buy them.
 You just create more disc image files.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By convention, these have names ending in 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

.dsk
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 So instead of having a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

manuscripts
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 disc, you would have a disc image file called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

manuscripts.dsk
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 To normal
\size small
 
\noun on
Unix 
\size default
\noun toggle
or Windows software, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

manuscripts.dsk
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is just one file, but PCW programs see it as a disc with any number of
 PCW files on it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One consequence of this is that the PCW's 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

A
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

B
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 drives have nothing to do with your PC's real floppy drives.
 The emulated PCW can be happily using a disc in its 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

B
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 drive even if your PC has only one drive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Converting your PCW discs to disc image files is covered in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: setup"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Disc image folders
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
JOYCE 2.1.8 and later can also use folders instead of disc image files.
 In this system, one PCW disc corresponds to one PC folder.
 This has the advantage that each PCW file corresponds exactly to one PC
 file.
 For example, you could instruct the PCW to make ASCII files, save them
 to such a disc/folder, and then read them directly with PC software.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Compiling JOYCE
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you have downloaded JOYCE as a binary for your platform (eg: the full
 Windows install, or an RPM), you can skip this section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To compile JOYCE, you will need:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
SDL, the Simple DirectMedia Layer: <http://www.libsdl.org>.
 You need version 1.0.8 or later.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
libxml, the xml parser used by GNOME <http://www.libxml.org/>.
 JOYCE was tested with version 2.2.6.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
libpng, the image library.
 <http://www.libpng.org/pub/png/>.
 You need version 1.0.6 or later.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You should be able to compile with the following commands: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
./configure
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
make
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
sudo make install 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On systems with a GCC version earlier than 3.0, the first line should be
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

./configure --with-ministl
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To cross-compile JOYCE for Windows, you need the XMINGW32 cross-compiler
 pack from <http://www.libsdl.org>, and MINGW32 versions of the above libraries.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
JOYCE on Mac OS X
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I have successfully compiled JOYCE on a Mac OS X (10.4.2) system.
 The process (and indeed MacOS X support in general) is pretty new and unpolishe
d.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Firstly, the three libraries mentioned above (SDL, libxml and libpng) had
 to be compiled from source and installed using their 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

make install
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 commands; pre-packaged OS X versions didn't seem to be suitable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Secondly, the configure script needed to be told what the host system was:
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
./configure --host=powerpc-darwin-apple8.2.2
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
make
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
sudo make install
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thirdly, this builds a JOYCE that is still very much a UNIX application;
 there's no application icon, no native OS X menu, and so on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, OS X uses the [f9] and [f10] keys for Exposé; so you will need
 to use [Command]+[F9] and [Command]+[F10] instead.
\end_layout

