\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: addboot"

\end_inset

Adding boot discs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first time JOYCE is started, it will detect that no boot discs have
 been read in.
 Unless you want to boot laboriously from a floppy every time you use JOYCE,
 you should choose the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

set up boot discs properly
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 option.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you had a previously working JOYCE installation, then this will be detected,
 and you will be given the option to copy boot discs from it.
 If you decide not to to this, you will have to provide start-of-day discs
 or disc image files.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next menu that appears asks you for the location of the boot disc to
 use.
 If you are using real floppies, then select the correct drive (A: or B:).
 If you are using pre-prepared DSK files, choose the correct file.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you are copying a MicroDesign program disc with copy protection (or other
 similar programs such as Tweak3), you will also need to click on 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Advanced
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 at this point and select the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

MicroDesign program disc
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 option.
 Note that this will not work on stock Windows NT, 2000 or XP; see section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: md3nt"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next select 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Continue
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 You will be asked for a name to give to this boot disc (eg: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

LocoScript
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

CP/M
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once you have entered the name, the disc is read in and converted to a JOYCE
 .DSK file.
 If you were copying from a real disc, you can put it away when the drive
 light goes out; JOYCE won't need it again.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You can then repeat for as many boot discs as you like.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you have trouble copying boot discs under Windows 95, 98 or ME, then
 see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "failread"

\end_inset

 which describes a workaround using PCWTRANS.
\end_layout

