\begin_layout Subsection
The LocoLink interface
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
JOYCE allows two forms of LocoLink communication (only one under Windows,
 though).
 In each case, you must have suitable software (LocoLink or PCWLink).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
LocoLink to a real computer (requires Linux)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For JOYCE to act as the slave computer, use a LapLink cable (not the original
 LocoLink cable) to connect the parallel ports of the two computers being
 linked.
 Go into the settings for the LocoLink interface, and set it to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Output to parallel port
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, specifying the name of the parallel port device (eg: /dev/parport0).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For JOYCE to act as the master, connect the parallel port of your Linux
 box to the other computer (if it's another PC, use a LapLink cable; if
 it's a PCW, use the original LocoLink cable).
 Go into the settings for the PAR port, and set it to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Output to parallel port
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, as above.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
LocoLink to another emulator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For JOYCE to act as the slave computer, go into the settings for the LocoLink
 interface and set it to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

output to Socket
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 On the screen that appears, select the correct socket type and name (see
 below) and ensure the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Server (LocoLink slave)
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 option is ticked.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For JOYCE to act as the master computer, go into the settings for the PAR
 port and set it to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

output to Socket
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 On the screen that appears, select the correct socket type and name (see
 below) and ensure the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Client (Normal)
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 option is ticked.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Socket types and names
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
UNIX
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

domain
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

sockets (not supported on Windows) can be used to communicate with other
 emulators on the same computer.
 They work pretty much like normal files, and their names are normal filenames;
 so, for example, one might be called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

/tmp/locolink.socket
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 When you are establishing a link, it is important that both ends are using
 the same socket name.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
TCP/IP
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

sockets can be used to communicate with other emulators not only on the
 same computer, but across a network or the Internet.
 However, JOYCE does not perform any security checks on socket connections,
 so I strongly recommend that you do not use TCP/IP sockets while connected
 to the Internet.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
For a LocoLink master, the name of a TCP/IP socket is formed 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

host:port
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 - for example, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

localhost:8256
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

127.0.0.1:8512
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or even 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

www.somewhere.com.invalid:8080
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a LocoLink slave, the name of the socket is formed 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

interface:port
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The interface is usually either 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

127.0.0.1
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (accept only connections from this computer) or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

0.0.0.0
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (accept connections from any computer).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The port has to be the same on both master and slave sides of the connection,
 and the host/interface have to refer to the same computer.
 For two emulators on the same computer, use 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

127.0.0.1:
\emph on
port
\emph default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for both master and slave.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
