\begin_layout Subsection
IMPORT
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
IMPORT will read UNIX files into the CP/M filesystem.
 It sets exact file sizes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The syntax is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
     IMPORT {/path/}hostfile            { [O] }
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
     IMPORT du:=/path/hostfile          { [O] }
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
     IMPORT du:cpmfile=x:/path/hostfile { [O] }
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first form imports the named file (or files) to the current drive and
 user area.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second form imports the file (or files) to the specified drive and user
 area, keeping the original name(s).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The third form imports the files, changing their name(s) to match the provided
 CP/M filename(s).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the [O] option is present, existing CP/M files with the same name as
 an imported file will be overwritten without asking.
 Otherwise you are asked for confirmation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both filenames may include wildcards, and the second and third forms can
 include CP/M driveletters and user numbers:
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
     A:IMPORT 
\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
     IMPORT>2F:*.ASC=/usr/doc/*.txt
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
will import all the .txt files in /usr/doc to drive F, group 2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Filenames are expanded case-sensitively, so you will normally need to use
 the backslash, as above, to get lower-case letters into the command line.
\end_layout

